TY  - JOUR
T1  - Old Is Gold? The Value of Temporal Exploration in the Creation of New Knowledge
AU  - Nerkar, Atul
Y1  - 2003/02/01
PY  - 2003
DA  - 2003/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.49.2.211.12747
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.49.2.211.12747
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 211
EP  - 229
VL  - 49
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In this paper, knowledge creation is considered as a path-dependent evolutionary process that involves recombining knowledge spread over time. The findings of the paper suggest that a balance in combining current knowledge with the knowledge available across large time spans is an important factor that explains the impact of new knowledge. These ideas are empirically tested using patent data from the pharmaceutical industry. Results from the analysis offer support for the hypotheses developed in the paper.
AB  - In this paper, knowledge creation is considered as a path-dependent evolutionary process that involves recombining knowledge spread over time. The findings of the paper suggest that a balance in combining current knowledge with the knowledge available across large time spans is an important factor that explains the impact of new knowledge. These ideas are empirically tested using patent data from the pharmaceutical industry. Results from the analysis offer support for the hypotheses developed in the paper.
